DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":1,"s":"D86 Grading Practices During Remote Learning Days

District 86 has created grading procedures that are based on guidance from the Illinois State Board of Education (ISBE), but also address and are respectful of the specific needs of our school community. 

ISBE has stated that the lowest grade a student can receive for second semester is what was listed in the Home Access Center (HAC) on Friday, March 13. Our goal is to continue providing quality instruction in conjunction with our Remote Learning Day (RLD) plan, and offer students opportunities to improve their grades. With that said, we understand and appreciate that those opportunities may be impacted if students do not have access to the same level of support that is typically available in a traditional school environment. We will continue to do our best to help our students overcome these challenges and remain engaged in learning during this time.

Regardless of the grades they had on March 13, all students are expected to complete the coursework they receive in conjunction with RLD. Those who do not could potentially receive a grade of Incomplete instead of what was posted in HAC prior to the closure of school. At the end of the school year, if a teacher does not have enough information to assign a grade that accurately reflects a students understanding of the key concepts in a course, the teacher may assign the student an Incomplete until such time as the student completes the required work. This practice aligns with guidance provided by ISBE. The following situations may contribute to this scenario:
The student is missing key work from the marking period prior to March 13, 2020
The student has a significant amount of unsubmitted work from the remote learning period
While we recognize that issuing an Incomplete is not ideal, this course of action reflects how critical the work we complete during RLD will be for preparing students for the content they will encounter next year either in our schools or in conjunction with their college or career experiences. For example, a student enrolled in Algebra 1 needs to be as prepared as possible to be successful in Geometry next year. If a grade of Incomplete is issued, an individualized remediation plan will be created to address the gaps in content knowledge that must be filled before a student can successfully access the next course.

Key Dates and Definitions
Marking period prior to the COVID-19 closure: January 7-March 13
ISBE Act of God Days: March 13-30
ISBE Remote Learning Days: March 30 to future (ISBE-determined) date
Frequently-Asked Questions
How will student RLD assessment work be scored and reported in HAC? 
Teachers may still differentiate between formative assignments (practice work) with a weight of 0 and summative assignments that contribute to a students grade. Formative assignments with a weight of 0 will not be included in a students grade calculation. Their primary purpose is to provide feedback about a students progress towards learning.
Teachers will record each students score on RLD assessments, regardless of whether that score increases or decreases a students grade. DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":4148,"s":"At the end of the marking period, teachers will compare the grade as of March 13, 2020 (found on the March 18 Interim Progress Report or IPR Tab in HAC) to the students current grade and determine if an override is necessary.
Remember, the lowest grade a student can receive for second semester is either their grade as of March 13, 2020 OR an Incomplete. If a students grade is an F at the end of the semester, ISBE recommends that it be changed to an Incomplete.
To indicate a student has Not Submitted coursework during the RLD, we have created a unique assignment score code, NS (No Submission). This code will be used beginning on April 1, 2020. The NS code will not be used for Act of God assignments from the time period of March 17-30, which will maintain a weight of 0 in HAC.

The NS code was created to help communicate the following information: 
The student did not submit the assignment
The assignment will be excluded from grade calculation 
How will incomplete/missing assignments/assessments from prior to March 13, 2020 be handled?
It is our goal to ensure that each students grade reflects what s/he knows or can do. Students will be asked to make up key assignments/assessments from prior to March 13, 2020 so that their grade accurately reflects their understanding. Teachers will be using their professional judgment to determine how to assess students during remote learning since they may not be able to re-assign/collect the same assignments that were originally done prior to March 13. If a students score on this make-up work negatively impacts their marking period grade as of March 13, 2020 (the grade shown on the March 18, 2020 IPR), this will be taken into account when assigning the cumulative grade for second semester
Why are letter grades (and not Passing/Incomplete grades) being used? 
We have worked hard over the past several years to establish a 1:1 learning environment in District 86. In that time, our teachers have been able to create mechanisms to both distribute and collect assessments. We feel this ability allows our teachers to continue to assess each students understanding in a way that allows them to make specific decisions about a students mastery that exceeds a simple Pass/Incomplete determination.
What if my student has difficulty completing a Remote Learning Assessment and that assessment negatively affects his/her performance?
Based on guidance from ISBE, the lowest grade a student can receive for second semester will either be the grade posted in HAC in the March 18, 2020 IPR, which reflects the students grade as of March 13, 2020, or an Incomplete as mentioned above. If students have concerns about individual assessments, they are encouraged to communicate those with their teachers. If they feel an RLD assessment does not accurately reflect their understanding, teachers may, at their discretion, provide students with further opportunities to demonstrate their mastery of a concept. 
How can parents/guardians and students find a students grade from March 13, 2020 (prior to remote learning)?
Parents/guardians and students can use HAC to access the March 18, 2020 IPR, which reflects the course letter grade as of March 13, 2020. 
For assistance in creating an account for HAC or accessing IPRs, please visit this users guide document. 
If you require assistance resetting your password for HAC, please consult this users guide document.
What is the schedule for RLD?
Until we receive further guidance from the ISBE, the following schedule will be used for remote learning in District 86:
Monday: Teacher Planning Day, Student Enrichment/Support
Teachers continue planning for remote learning lessons
No classes meet; students do not need to check in for attendance purposes
Students work on various enrichment opportunities, as needed
PSAT-aligned Khan Academy lessons
AP College-Board Test-Prep

On Remote Learning Days, students should continue to do the following:
Log in to the Canvas Learning Management system prior to the start of each class on a daily basis (schedule featured in the table below).
After signing in to Canvas, complete the Google Check-in Form in the Remote Learning Day Module. This will be done for each class that is in session that day (schedule featured in the table below). Students should NOT check in for all of their classes in advance. 
Complete assignments found within the Remote Learning Day Module for each class that is in session that day. In some cases, your teacher may be leading the class remotely through a streaming platform like Google Hangouts Meet or Canvas Conferences. With this in mind, it will be especially important to make sure students sign in to Canvas on time on the days when whole class sessions are taking place. Teachers will indicate when these sessions are being held by using the phrase whole class in the title of the assignment. 
Communicate with the teacher if students have questions or experience any issues/problems.
